label.value: normal pathogen growth after penetration of the barrier

definition.value: A single species phenotype in which the pathogen's ability to contine to grow after penetration of a given experimental substance/membrane in an in vitro assay is normal (i.e indistinguishable from wild type).

label.value: normal formation of pathogen penetration structure

definition.value: A single species pathogen growth phenotype in which the formation of the pathogen penetration structure is normal (i.e same as wild-type) when assessed for penetration ability on a given experimental substance/membrane.

label.value: pathogen penetration across the barrier absent

definition.value: A single species pathogen penetration phenotype in which pathogen penetration of a given experimental substance/membrane is absent.

label.value: abnormal pathogen growth after penetration of the barrier

definition.value: A single species phenotype in which the pathogen's ability to contine to grow after penetration of a given experimental substance/membrane in an in vitro assay is abnormal (i.e indistinguishable from wild type).

label.value: abnormal formation of pathogen penetration structure

definition.value: A single species pathogen growth phenotype in which the formation of the pathogen penetration structure is abnormal (i.e different than wild-type) when assessed for penetration ability on a given experimental substance/membrane.
A single species phenotype that is observed at the level of an individual cell.
A pathogen host phenotype where the mutualism phenotype is normal (i.e. the same as wild-type), and the wild-type interaction exhibits mutualism.
A single organism phenotype observed in the vegetative growth phase of the life cycle in which the size, shape, or structure of lipid droplets is abnormal.

A phenotype which affects the balance of symbiotic mutualism, mutualism describes an interaction between two symbionts (where the larger is usually the host), results in positive (beneficial) effects on reproduction and/or survival of both species.
A phenotype in which the interaction is the same as the wild-type, no asymptomatic colonisation or disease formation symptoms are visible.
A phenotype in which the balance of symbiotic mutualism has been disrupted compared to the normal interaction.
A single species phenotype where reproduction is abnormal.
A single species phenotype where reproduction is normal (indistinguishable from wild type).

A single species phenotype where the asexual reproduction process in which new individuals are produced by either a single cell or a group of cells, in the absence of any sexual process is normal (indistinguishable from wild type)(GO:0019954).

A single species phenotype where the sexual reproduction process in which new individuals are produced by combining the genetic material of two gametes, which may come from two organisms or from a single organism is normal (indistinguishable from wild type) (GO:0019953).

A single species phenotype where the asexual reproduction process in which new individuals are produced by either a single cell or a group of cells, in the absence of any sexual process is abnormal (GO:0019954).

A single species phenotype where the sexual reproduction process in which new individuals are produced by combining the genetic material of two gametes, which may come from two organisms or from a single organism is abnormal (GO:0019953).
A population phenotype in which the frequency of occurrence of sexual spores is increased.
A population phenotype in which the frequency of occurrence of sexual spores is decreased.
A population phenotype in which the frequency of occurrence of asexual spores is increased.
A population phenotype in which the frequency of occurrence of asexual spores is decreased.
A reproductive phenotype in which the occurrence of asexual spore formation happens later than normal.
A reproductive phenotype in which the occurrence of asexual spore formation happens sooner than normal.
A reproductive phenotype in which the occurrence of sexual spore formation happens later than normal.
A reproductive phenotype in which the occurrence of sexual spore formation happens sooner than normal.
A population phenotype in which the frequency of occurrence of sexual spores is normal  (i.e. indistinguishable from wild type).
A population phenotype in which the frequency of occurrence of asexual spores is normal  (i.e. indistinguishable from wild type).
A reproductive phenotype where asexual spores are absent (FAO:0000023).
A reproductive phenotype where sexual spores are absent (FAO:0000017).
A reproductive phenotype where asexual spores are present (FAO:0000017). The product of meiosis.
A reproductive phenotype where asexual spores are present (FAO:0000023). The product of mitosis.
A reproductive morphology phenotype where the size of the asexual spore is increased.
A reproductive morphology phenotype where the size of the asexual spore is decreased.
A reproductive morphology phenotype where the size of the sexual spore is increased.
A reproductive morphology phenotype where the size of the sexual spore is decreased.

label.value: altered in pigment accumulation in sexual spore

definition.value: A single species individual organism phenotype where the accumulation of coloring matter in a sexual spore cell is altered.
A reproductive morphology phenotype where the size of the sexual spore is abnormal.
A reproductive morphology phenotype where the shape of the sexual spore is abnormal.
A population phenotype in which the frequency of occurrence of sexual spores is abnormal.
A reproductive morphology phenotype where the shape of the asexual spore is abnormal.

label.value: altered in pigment accumulation in asexual spore

definition.value: A single species individual organism phenotype where the accumulation of coloring matter in an asexual spore cell is altered.

A reproductive phenotype where the process of asexual sporulation, the formation of spores derived from the products of an asexual cell division, is abnormal (GO:0030436).
A reproductive phenotype where the process of sexual sporulation, the formation of spores from the products of meiosis, is normal (GO:0034293).
A reproductive phenotype where the process of asexual sporulation, the formation of spores derived from the products of an asexual cell division, is normal (GO:0030436).
A reproductive morphology phenotype where the size of the asexual spore is abnormal.
A population phenotype in which the frequency of occurrence of asexual spores is abnormal.

A reproductive process phenotype in which the first meiotic nuclear division is abnormal (GO:0007127).
A reproductive process phenotype in which the second meiotic nuclear division is normal (i.e. indistinguishable from wild type)(GO:0007135).
